[1] France
Date: Fri 29 Sep 2017
Source: Silver Times [edited]
https://sivertimes.com/measles-405-case-in-france-since-the-beginning-of-the-year/70769


Between January and July [2017], more than 400 people have been infected [with measles]. In particular, an outbreak occurred in the month of May 2017. This increased the alarm of public health in France. In the past year [2016], only 79 cases had been identified.

It must be said that measles is active and virulent. In total, 168 patients were hospitalized because of the infection, most often for severe pneumonia. Evidence that the virus does not distinguish between its victims, a 16 year-old girl died of severe complications in July 2017. She was non-vaccinated; however, she had no previous medical history.

Most of the time, these are young children who bear the brunt of the infection. Infants under 1 year and children 1-4 years of age are among the main reported cases; next, adolescents 15-19 years.

Kindergartens, schools and universities are among the privileged places of measles transmission.

Public Health France considers it necessary to prepare for an outbreak. "The current epidemiology of measles shows that France is still endemic and is not immune to a new outbreak of significant [size]." In fact, the [cases] are distributed rather evenly in the territory.

The scenario of an epidemic is all the more credible because the immunization coverage is so low. Only 79 percent of babies 2 years old are vaccinated. It would be necessary to reach 95 percent in order to prevent any movement of the virus.

In the light of these indicators, public Health France recommends that healthcare professionals be vigilant. If the [vaccine series] is incomplete, a vaccination catch-up or post-exposure prophylaxis will prevent the spread of the virus.

The goal: prevent an epidemic like that of 2011 [see figure showing number of case yearly in report at URL]. In the space of a year, more than 15 000 people had been infected; 10 deaths were recorded.

France is [not alone] in the face of this resurgence of measles. Our neighbours -- Italians, Belgians and Germans -- have been faced with a sudden increase in cases. Because of this, Italy has chosen to re-establish the vaccination requirement. Further to the east, Romania must also combat an outbreak that is very active.

--
